Boston Metropolitan Bicycle Mobility 4.0¶

Keywords¶

keywords=["bikesharing", "Boston", "BlueBikes", "transportation 4.0", "mobility"]

Purpose¶

The Massachusetts state department of transportation recognized that even for relatively small trips automobiles are being used throughout the state. The department has decided to encourage the use of bicycles and make cities more bicycle friendly. Keeping in mind the increasing population and lack of space in Boston the state wants to encourage people to become everyday cyclists in Boston. They also want to promote health and wellbeing and curb greenhouse gas emissions from vehicles. Boston has a bikesharing service called Bluebikes which is becoming an integral part of the citys public transit network. We want to help the state rethink bicycle mobility in Boston by proposing improvements such that the bikeshare network can benefit from the business distribution in the city. We would do that by analyzing the following questions.

Questions:

  1. Does the concentration and type of businesses in a particular ZIP code correlate with the number of Bluebikes trips in that area?
  2. Does this change if we look at the different user types (subscription vs. one-off riders)?

Methodology¶

In order to answer the questions above, we mainly utilize four datasets. The first dataset is Bluebikes Trip Data, which contains user trip data from June - August 2021. The next datasets are the Foursquare-Venues and Foursquare-Categories dataset, to analyze business in Boston with respect to their ZIP code, type of business and categories. Lastly, we use the zipcode dataset to map locations and zones across the Foursquare and Bluebikes datasets.

Further we have carried out the following tasks in order to answer our business questions:

  • Data Dictionary: We identified 4 datasets and created a data dictionary in order to store information about our data such as meaning, relationships to other data, origin, usage, and format.

  • Database Setup and Data preparation:

    1. Normalization of the database resulted in a set of 5 tables from the input dataset of 4 tables. The ZIP code and Foursquare were already in normal format. For those datasets the relevant columns for the analysis were kept and the ones not relevant were dropped. The Bluebikes dataset is at the 2nd normal form and to facilitate handling in the database, it was split into 2 tables to transform into 3rd normal form. As with the other datasets, the relevant columns for the analysis were kept and the ones not relevant were dropped [Section 10-Appendix]

    2. After normalization we created our tables in pgadmin, connected to our AWS database and loaded our data into the tables.

  • Exploratory Data Analysis: We carried out exploratory data analysis on our data by establishing a connection with our AWS database, using sql queries and python libraries.

    1. We produced cross-plots in order to understand the data, with possible trends to formulate the initial modeling hypothesis. Cross plots include count of venues and count of trips, count of stations and count of trips and the count of stations and count of venues [Section 7.2.1- Graph 1,2,3]. For each of those charts, each data point is an aggregation of the data into a ZIP code.

    2. We produced a correlation matrix to check the correlation between number of trips number of venues and the correlation between number of trips and the number of stations[Section 7.2.1- Table 1]

  • Analysis: As the final step, we analyzed the data in order to identify the number of venues in each category and checked if it correlates with a higher usage of Bluebikes service across every ZIP code. We also assesed if this changes when we look at the different user types (subscription vs. one-off riders).

    1. To understand if the concentration of any specific type of venue has a stronger correlation with the trip, the count of each type of venue was plotted against the number of trips and the correlation matrix was calculated [Section 7.2.2-Graph 4, Table 2]

    2. Just looking at the correlation matrix can be misleading for this analysis as venues that show stronger correlation are not necessarily wide spread throughout the city. To assess this, a coverage list was calculated to see what percentage of the zip codes that trips also had each type of venue [Section 7.2.2-Table 3]

    3. We use linear regression (target= number of stations, independent variables= number of trips and number of the selected venues) to verify which areas are overserved and underserved. Results were then placed in a cluster and mapped to easily visualize which ones are underserved and overserved [Section 7.2.2- Figure 1]

    4. Similar analysis was performed with the trip broken down between subscribers and non-subcribers [Section 7.2.3- Figure 2, Figure 3]

  • Summary of Findings: Lastly, we discuss our results, provide our recommendations and identify potential limitations with our analysis [Section 5 and Section 6]

Datasets and Data Dictionary¶

Datasets and updated Data Dictionary is attached as a supplemental file.

Results¶

  • The number of trips are positively correlated to the count of venues in each zip code. (corr = 0.519) [Section 7.2.1]
  • Out of different catergories of venues, "College_University", "Food", "NightlifeSpot" and "Outdoors_Recreation" are the most correlated to the number of trips in a Zip Code [Section 7.2.2-Graph 4, Table 2]
  • However, the coverage (i.e % of districts that have at least 1 venue of given category) of "College_University" is very poor (13.7%) whereas "Food" (100%), "NightlifeSpot" (84.31%) and Outdoors_Recreation (98.03%) have high coverage across zip codes [Section 7.2.2-Table 3]
  • As per the regression model for predicted number of stations on the basis of venues [Section 7.2.2- Figure 1]
    • Bluebikes should install more stations in Downtown and the sub-urban regions of Boston
    • Bluebikes should incentivise bike usage in Cambridge, Somerville and Chelsea -Subscribed Customers: Most stations in Metro Boston have similar service level for subscribed customers as for all customers [Section 7.2.3] -Unsubscribed Customers: They show similar trend to the underserved/overserved station map for all customers [Section 7.2.3]

Conclusion¶

In conclusion, we noticed that outdoor recreation, nightlife spots and food business areas correlate with a higher usage of Bluebikes number of trips. We recommend adding more stations in such areas based on zip-code- Downtown and the sub-urban regions of Boston but we cannot pinpoint exact location, number of stations and number of bikes since that would require further analysis.

In terms of subscribers and one-time users we observed underserved areas and we recommend the following:

  • Bluebikes should install more stations in Downtown and the sub-urban regions of Boston
  • Bluebikes should incentivise bike usage in Cambridge, Somerville and Chelsea

Our analysis is based on publicly available data, we could also use proprietary data to dig deeper into the exact locations that need to be expanded either by increasing stations or number of bikes.

Limitations

  • The Bluebikes dataset used for this research project was collected from June to August 2021. This may not be enough data to base final decisions on, as for example yearly seasonality effects could not be analyzed and possible impacts of COVID-19 could not be gauged.
  • It was assumed that the Foursquare dataset identifies all business types correctly, that it includes all businesses in Boston and is up to date.
  • Overall, no outside effects such as for example the overall city growth, new housing developments, urban planning initiatives,topography etc. have been considered in this analysis.

For this analysis pandas, numpy, matplotlib, sklearn, folium, os, psycopg2 and dotenv libraries were used. As presented in the code below, those were used to import, manipulate and visualize the data.

Data import¶

As mentioned previously, the data for this analysis is sourced from Bluebikes, Foursquare, and zip codes. In order to be able to compare and make inferences all data was brought to the zip code level. In order to do that, the zip code table was used as starting point to ensure that we cover all areas of metro Boston, even if those are not covered by bluebikes currently or there's no venues on the zip code area as per fourquare. To this initial table the agregated count trips, the different types of trips, venues and specific venue categories were joined together to compose the data table used in the analysis. The diagram below shows how the datasets were combined to create the data table for the analysis.

Connection with database¶

The data for this analysis is stored in a postgresql as presented previously. To be able to load the data, the initial step is to create a connection with the database.

In [2]:
load_dotenv()
# Create a connection
conString = {'host':os.environ.get('DB_HOST'),
             'dbname':os.environ.get('DB_NAME'),
             'user':os.environ.get('DB_USER'),
             'password':os.environ.get('DB_PASS'),

conn = psycopg2.connect(**conString)
# Create a cursor
cur = conn.cursor()

Importing the data table¶

After the connection is stablished, the data table can be imported as described. We decided to join the Bluebikes data on the start station for this report as there was no significant difference in the results compared to when joining on the end station.

In [3]:
#Formulate Query
query = """select stations, trip_count, trip_not_subscriber, trip_subscriber,ZIPcode, latitude, longitude, venue_count, Art_Entertainment, College_University, Events, Food, NightlifeSpot, Outdoors_Recreation, Professional_OtherPlaces, Residence, Shop_Service, Travel_Transport  from
(select trip_count, trip_not_subscriber, trip_subscriber, stations, bbb.postalcode as postalcode from
(select count(boston_project.bluebike_station.id1) as stations, postalcode1 
	from boston_project.bluebike_station group by postalcode1) as bbs
right join
(select trip_count, trip_not_subscriber, trip_subscriber, bbt.postalcode as postalcode from
(select count(bluebike.trip) as trip_count, bluebike.postalcode as postalcode
	from (select boston_project.bluebike_trip.id as trip, boston_project.bluebike_station.postalcode1 as postalcode from
		 boston_project.bluebike_trip join boston_project.bluebike_station 
		 	on boston_project.bluebike_trip.start_station=boston_project.bluebike_station.id1) as bluebike
	group by bluebike.postalcode) as bbt
left join
(select trip_not_subscriber, trip_subscriber, bbc.postalcode as postalcode from
(select count(bluebike.trip) as trip_not_subscriber, bluebike.postalcode as postalcode
	from (select boston_project.bluebike_trip.id as trip, boston_project.bluebike_trip.usertype, boston_project.bluebike_station.postalcode1 as postalcode from
		 boston_project.bluebike_trip join boston_project.bluebike_station 
		 	on boston_project.bluebike_trip.start_station=boston_project.bluebike_station.id1) as bluebike
 	where bluebike.usertype='Customer'
	group by bluebike.postalcode) as bbc
full join
(select count(bluebike.trip) as trip_subscriber, bluebike.postalcode as postalcode
	from (select boston_project.bluebike_trip.id as trip, boston_project.bluebike_trip.usertype, boston_project.bluebike_station.postalcode1 as postalcode from
		 boston_project.bluebike_trip join boston_project.bluebike_station 
		 	on boston_project.bluebike_trip.start_station=boston_project.bluebike_station.id1) as bluebike
 	where bluebike.usertype='Subscriber'
	group by bluebike.postalcode) as bbs
on bbc.postalcode = bbs.postalcode) as bbu
on bbt.postalcode = bbu.postalcode) as bbb
on bbs.postalcode1 = bbb.postalcode) as bb
right join
-- Join 11
--Total
(select venue_count, Art_Entertainment, College_University, Events, Food, NightlifeSpot, Outdoors_Recreation, Professional_OtherPlaces, Residence, Shop_Service, Travel_Transport, ZIPcode, latitude, longitude from
(select count(boston_project.foursquare_venues.fsv_id) as venue_count, boston_project.foursquare_venues.postalcode as postalcode 
 	from boston_project.foursquare_venues join boston_project.foursquare_categories 
		on boston_project.foursquare_venues.category = boston_project.foursquare_categories.fs_id
 group by boston_project.foursquare_venues.postalcode) as venue
right join
-- Join 10
(select Art_Entertainment, College_University, Events, Food, NightlifeSpot, Outdoors_Recreation, Professional_OtherPlaces, Residence, Shop_Service, Travel_Transport, ZIPcode, latitude, longitude from
--Arts&Entertainment
(select count(boston_project.foursquare_venues.fsv_id) as Art_Entertainment, boston_project.foursquare_venues.postalcode as postalcode 
 	from boston_project.foursquare_venues join boston_project.foursquare_categories 
		on boston_project.foursquare_venues.category = boston_project.foursquare_categories.fs_id
	where boston_project.foursquare_categories.CAT_Level0 = 'Arts & Entertainment'
 group by boston_project.foursquare_venues.postalcode) as AE
right join
-- Join 9
(select College_University, Events, Food, NightlifeSpot, Outdoors_Recreation, Professional_OtherPlaces, Residence, Shop_Service, Travel_Transport, ZIPcode, latitude, longitude from
--College&University
(select count(boston_project.foursquare_venues.fsv_id) as College_University, boston_project.foursquare_venues.postalcode as postalcode 
 	from boston_project.foursquare_venues join boston_project.foursquare_categories 
		on boston_project.foursquare_venues.category = boston_project.foursquare_categories.fs_id
	where boston_project.foursquare_categories.CAT_Level0 = 'College & University'
 group by boston_project.foursquare_venues.postalcode) as CU
right join
-- Join 8
(select Events, Food, NightlifeSpot, Outdoors_Recreation, Professional_OtherPlaces, Residence, Shop_Service, Travel_Transport, ZIPcode, latitude, longitude from
--Event
(select count(boston_project.foursquare_venues.fsv_id) as Events, boston_project.foursquare_venues.postalcode as postalcode 
 	from boston_project.foursquare_venues join boston_project.foursquare_categories 
		on boston_project.foursquare_venues.category = boston_project.foursquare_categories.fs_id
	where boston_project.foursquare_categories.CAT_Level0 = 'Event'
 group by boston_project.foursquare_venues.postalcode) as EV
right join
-- Join 7
(select Food, NightlifeSpot, Outdoors_Recreation, Professional_OtherPlaces, Residence, Shop_Service, Travel_Transport, ZIPcode, latitude, longitude from
--Food
(select count(boston_project.foursquare_venues.fsv_id) as Food, boston_project.foursquare_venues.postalcode as postalcode 
 	from boston_project.foursquare_venues join boston_project.foursquare_categories 
		on boston_project.foursquare_venues.category = boston_project.foursquare_categories.fs_id
	where boston_project.foursquare_categories.CAT_Level0 = 'Food'
 group by boston_project.foursquare_venues.postalcode) as FD
right join
-- Join 6
(select NightlifeSpot, Outdoors_Recreation, Professional_OtherPlaces, Residence, Shop_Service, Travel_Transport, ZIPcode, latitude, longitude from
--NightlifeSpot
(select count(boston_project.foursquare_venues.fsv_id) as NightlifeSpot, boston_project.foursquare_venues.postalcode as postalcode 
 	from boston_project.foursquare_venues join boston_project.foursquare_categories 
		on boston_project.foursquare_venues.category = boston_project.foursquare_categories.fs_id
	where boston_project.foursquare_categories.CAT_Level0 = 'Nightlife Spot'
 group by boston_project.foursquare_venues.postalcode) as NS
right join
-- Join 5
(select Outdoors_Recreation, Professional_OtherPlaces, Residence, Shop_Service, Travel_Transport, ZIPcode, latitude, longitude from
--Outdoors&Recreation
(select count(boston_project.foursquare_venues.fsv_id) as Outdoors_Recreation, boston_project.foursquare_venues.postalcode as postalcode 
 	from boston_project.foursquare_venues join boston_project.foursquare_categories 
		on boston_project.foursquare_venues.category = boston_project.foursquare_categories.fs_id
	where boston_project.foursquare_categories.CAT_Level0 = 'Outdoors & Recreation'
 group by boston_project.foursquare_venues.postalcode) as ORc
right join
-- Join 4
(select Professional_OtherPlaces, Residence, Shop_Service, Travel_Transport, ZIPcode, latitude, longitude from
--Professional & Other Places
(select count(boston_project.foursquare_venues.fsv_id) as Professional_OtherPlaces, boston_project.foursquare_venues.postalcode as postalcode 
 	from boston_project.foursquare_venues join boston_project.foursquare_categories 
		on boston_project.foursquare_venues.category = boston_project.foursquare_categories.fs_id
	where boston_project.foursquare_categories.CAT_Level0 = 'Professional & Other Places'
 group by boston_project.foursquare_venues.postalcode) as PO
right join
-- Join 3
(select Residence, Shop_Service, Travel_Transport, ZIPcode, latitude, longitude from
--Residence
(select count(boston_project.foursquare_venues.fsv_id) as Residence, boston_project.foursquare_venues.postalcode as postalcode 
 	from boston_project.foursquare_venues join boston_project.foursquare_categories 
		on boston_project.foursquare_venues.category = boston_project.foursquare_categories.fs_id
	where boston_project.foursquare_categories.CAT_Level0 = 'Residence'
 group by boston_project.foursquare_venues.postalcode) as Res
right join
-- Join 2
(select Shop_Service, Travel_Transport, ZIPcode, latitude, longitude from
--Shop&Service
(select count(boston_project.foursquare_venues.fsv_id) as Shop_Service, boston_project.foursquare_venues.postalcode as postalcode 
 	from boston_project.foursquare_venues join boston_project.foursquare_categories 
		on boston_project.foursquare_venues.category = boston_project.foursquare_categories.fs_id
	where boston_project.foursquare_categories.CAT_Level0 = 'Shop & Service'
 group by boston_project.foursquare_venues.postalcode) as SS
right join
-- Join 1
 (select boston_project.postal_code.postalcode as ZIPcode, boston_project.postal_code.latitude as latitude, boston_project.postal_code.longitude as longitude , Travel_Transport from
--Travel&Transport
(select count(boston_project.foursquare_venues.fsv_id) as Travel_Transport, boston_project.foursquare_venues.postalcode as postalcode
 	from boston_project.foursquare_venues join boston_project.foursquare_categories 
		on boston_project.foursquare_venues.category = boston_project.foursquare_categories.fs_id
	where boston_project.foursquare_categories.CAT_Level0 = 'Travel & Transport'
 group by boston_project.foursquare_venues.postalcode) as TT
right join 
boston_project.postal_code
on TT.postalcode = boston_project.postal_code.postalcode) as J1
on SS.postalcode = J1.ZIPcode) as J2
on Res.postalcode = J2.ZIPcode) as J3
on PO.postalcode = J3.ZIPcode) as J4
on ORc.postalcode = J4.ZIPcode) as J5
on NS.postalcode = J5.ZIPcode) as J6
on FD.postalcode = J6.ZIPcode) as J7
on EV.postalcode = J7.ZIPcode) as J8
on CU.postalcode = J8.ZIPcode) as J9
on AE.postalcode = J9.ZIPcode) as J10
on venue.postalcode = J10.ZIPcode) as J11
on bb.postalcode = J11.ZIPcode
"""

Analysis¶

This analysis is split in three parts:

  • Inspection of the data
  • Analysis of the total trips
  • Analysis of the subscribers and non-subscribers trips

Inspection of the data¶

The source data consists of 9,193 venues, 978,710 trips and 409 bike stations spread over 84 zip codes. The number of data points allows us to comfortably perform the analysis and detect general trends.

In order to understand the data, with possible trends to formulate the initial modeling hypothesis, we created some cross-plots. Those are the cross-plots between count of venues and count of trips, count of stations and count of trips and the count of stations and count of venues. For each of those charts, each data point is an aggregation of the data into a ZIP code.

The charts and the correlation matrix clearly show that some types of venues have a stronger relationship with trips and others. However, just looking at the correlation matrix can be misleading for this analysis as venues that show stronger correlation are not necessarily wide spread throughout the city and thus using it can lead to reducing the scope of bluebikes instead of moving towards making it more accessible. To assess this, a coverage list was calculated to see what percentage of the zip codes that trips also had each type of venue.

In [10]:
print("Table 3")
coverage = []
for i in range(0,len(CAT0)):
    coverage.append(fs_bb_allzipcodes[fs_bb_allzipcodes['trip_count'].notnull()][CAT0[i]].count()/fs_bb_allzipcodes[fs_bb_allzipcodes['trip_count'].notnull()]['trip_count'].count())
    
DC = {'CAT':CAT0, 'Coverage': coverage}
All_trips_Coverage = pd.DataFrame(DC)

From the analysis so far, we narrow the types of venues to Food, Night Life Sports and Outdoors & Recreation as those are present in most places and have a relevant relationship with the number of trips.

Modeling over the relevant venues

To verify which areas are overserved and underserved we ran a liner regression using the number of stations as target variable with the number of trips and number of the selected venues as the independent variables.

In [11]:
fs_bb_allzipcodes['FNO'] = fs_bb_allzipcodes['Food'].fillna(0)+fs_bb_allzipcodes['NightlifeSpot'].fillna(0)+fs_bb_allzipcodes['Outdoors_Recreation'].fillna(0)

regr_station_FNO = linear_model.LinearRegression()
regr_station_FNO_data = fs_bb_allzipcodes[['stations','trip_count','FNO']].dropna()
x = regr_station_FNO_data[['trip_count','FNO']]
y = regr_station_FNO_data[['stations']]
regr_station_FNO.fit(x,y)
regr_station_FNO.score(x,y)
Out[11]:
0.5141170131253688
In [12]:
fs_bb_allzipcodes['trip_count'] = fs_bb_allzipcodes['trip_count'].fillna(0)
fs_bb_allzipcodes['station_pred'] = regr_station_FNO.predict(fs_bb_allzipcodes[['trip_count','FNO']])
fs_bb_allzipcodes['station_pred'] = fs_bb_allzipcodes['station_pred'].round(2)
fs_bb_allzipcodes[['station_pred','stations','trip_count','Food','NightlifeSpot','Outdoors_Recreation']]

The results were then placed in a cluster and mapped to easily visualize which ones are underserved and overserved.

In [13]:
print("Figure 1")

# Labeling the zip codes
lst = []
for i in range(0,len(fs_bb_allzipcodes)):
    if fs_bb_allzipcodes['stations'][i]>fs_bb_allzipcodes['station_pred'][i]:
        lst.append(1)
    else:
        lst.append(0)
fs_bb_allzipcodes['Cluster_allTrips'] = pd.DataFrame(lst)

# Generating map with results
latitude = fs_bb_allzipcodes['latitude'].mean()
longitude = fs_bb_allzipcodes['longitude'].mean()
rainbow = ['#8000ff', '#ff0000']
map_clusters = folium.Map(location=[latitude, longitude], zoom_start=11)

for lat, lon,station, Pred_stat, fno, trip, zipcode, cluster in zip(fs_bb_allzipcodes['latitude'], fs_bb_allzipcodes['longitude'], fs_bb_allzipcodes['stations'], fs_bb_allzipcodes['station_pred'], fs_bb_allzipcodes['FNO'], fs_bb_allzipcodes['trip_count'], fs_bb_allzipcodes['ZIPcode'], fs_bb_allzipcodes['Cluster_allTrips']):
    label = folium.Popup('Stations '+str(station)+'\n' +
                         'Predicted '+str(Pred_stat)+'\n' +
                         'Trips '+str(trip)+'\n' +
                         'Venues '+str(fno)+'\n' +
                         'ZIP Code '+str(zipcode)+'\n' +
                         '\nCluster ' + str(cluster), parse_html=True)
    folium.CircleMarker(
        [lat, lon],
        radius=10,
        popup=label,
        color=rainbow[cluster-1],
        fill=True,
        fill_color=rainbow[cluster-1],
        fill_opacity=0.7).add_to(map_clusters)
       
map_clusters

Figure 1
Out[13]:
Make this Notebook Trusted to load map: File -> Trust Notebook

As presented in the map, the areas close to downtown are generally overserved while the area in the suburbs are underserved.
